{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_015yvWz2qu8RDiqgiqtVrTt3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it. Line 718-719 in ralph.sh:\n```bash\ncp \"sprint-state.json\" \"$state_snapshot_path\" 2>/dev/null || true\n```\n\nRalph snapshots sprint-state.json at the START of each iteration. But the snapshot has `done: 70` and stories at `review`. This means the snapshot is being taken BEFORE the harness-run session fixes the state, and then... let me check if the snapshot is being restored.\n\nActually wait — the snapshot has `done: 70` and the stories at review. The snapshot is being copied FROM sprint-state.json. \n\nSo sprint-state.json itself has the wrong values. That means something is writing sprint-state.json with the old values. Let me trace through what ralph actually calls — it's invoking `claude` directly, not `codeharness run`, so the reconcileState() that normally runs on session start isn't being triggered. I need to figure out what command ralph is using and whether state reconciliation is happening at all.\n\nThe real issue is that something keeps rewriting sprint-state.json back to `review` statuses even after the session fix changes them to `done`. I'm wondering if `codeharness progress` or some cleanup step at the end of a session is reverting the state, or if ralph.sh's state snapshot mechanism is being used to restore old values somehow.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1043,"cache_read_input_tokens":45570,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1043},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"38034db4-332c-4e74-ba93-5458d26240ee"}
