{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013VX12BMFQ2Aaqb6ewAaaHN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see it more clearly. Let me check `writeSprintStatusYaml` — line 558 calls it even when `changed` is `false`. This means EVERY reconciliation call regenerates the YAML from sprint-state.json. So the YAML is derived from state. That's fine.\n\nBut the real question is: why does sprint-state.json have `review` for those 4 stories? The session issues say previous sessions fixed them to `done`. \n\nThe snapshot file `ralph/.state-snapshot.json` has `done: 70` which matches the pre-fix state. Maybe ralph is restoring the snapshot somehow?\n \nActually, looking at the ralph.sh code more carefully — the snapshot is being written TO, not read FROM. So that's not the restore source. But I'm wondering if ralph is reading sprint-state.json to pick the next story, finding those `review` entries, and then the harness-run session tries to process them. Let me trace through how sprint-state.json gets written in the first place and whether `writeStateAtomic` or `writeSprintStatusYaml` could be introducing these wrong values.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4276,"cache_read_input_tokens":48895,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4276},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"ab93afda-0ed1-484f-9a40-8984f0dd8ee2"}
