{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013K16tCkqsUZ8h6ESJf15c9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I found it. `updateRunProgress` and `clearRunProgress` both:\n\n1. Call `getSprintState()` — reads sprint-state.json from disk\n2. Spread the current state\n3. Call `writeStateAtomic()` — writes state back to disk AND regenerates YAML\n\nThis is a read-modify-write cycle. If the harness-run session edits sprint-state.json using the Edit tool (which modifies the file in place), and THEN calls `codeharness progress --clear` or `codeharness progress --story ...`, the progress command will:\n\n\n1. Read the updated sprint-state.json with the fixed `done` statuses\n2. Update the run progress fields\n3. Write it back\n\nThat should preserve the story statuses unless `getSprintState()` is caching the data somewhere.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":676,"cache_read_input_tokens":67327,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":676},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"ce67a682-dad6-43d5-9823-88ebdda3fde3"}
