{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JrNX4sDXfUPswN1VtUCbuG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK! Now I see the full picture. The committed version has:\n- `sprint.done: 70` (not 74)\n- Story 16-8 has `lastAttempt: null` and `proofPath: null`\n- Epic 16 has `status: \"in-progress\"` and `storiesDone: 7`\n- Epic 14 has `storiesDone: 4` (should be 7)\n\nBut the committed version DOES have all 8 stories in epic 16 at status `done`. That's the key part.\n\nThe diff shows the working tree changes (my fixes from this session + the previous session's fixes). \n\nSo the previous session had already modified sprint-state.json before this one started, but I'm wondering if `codeharness run` calls `reconcileState()` between sessions, which reads and writes the file back — and maybe that's reverting some of the fields somehow. Let me trace through what the committed version actually contains versus what's in the working tree now.\n\nThe commit itself was inconsistent — all the stories show as done, but sprint.done is 70 instead of 74, and Epic 16 is marked in-progress with storiesDone: 7. When I look at the reconcileState function, it merges retries and flagged stories, imports from YAML if needed, validates epic consistency, and regenerates the YAML output, but it doesn't actually recalculate the sprint.done or epic storiesDone counts. So if the committed version had those wrong values, reconcileState wouldn't fix them.\n\nNow I'm wondering whether writeSprintStatusYaml() generates the YAML from the actual story statuses or from the sprint.done summary count — that's what would determine whether the YAML output reflects the real state or perpetuates the wrong counts.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":651,"cache_read_input_tokens":71531,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":651},"output_