{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PpiARCH3zGJiRpn76nK23A","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so I see the polling interval at line 243 (every 5 seconds). But this is read-only — it calls `getSprintState()` and `readSprintStatusFromState()` but never writes back.\n\nBut wait — line 265-266: `child.kill('SIGTERM')` — this can kill the claude session prematurely. But that's the deferral logic, not relevant here.\n\nThe `createDriverLineHandler` at line 238 handles events from the driver. The events include `story-complete` (line 41) which calls `updateStoryStatus(event.key, 'review')`. \n\nSo the driver emits `story-complete` when it detects certain patterns in the output stream — the flow is `codeharness run` spawns ralph, which spawns claude sessions that write to stdout, and the driver's line handler parses that output to emit events based on what it sees.\n\nWhen a `story-complete` event fires, it sets the story to `review` status, not `done` — that's intentional since stories need code review after development. The real concern is whether NO_WORK sessions are somehow triggering these events if their output happens to match the story-complete pattern. I need to look at what patterns `createDriverLineHandler` is actually checking for.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2323,"cache_read_input_tokens":74170,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2323},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"d6ce5ecb-54d9-4c65-931d-2b24413dd224"}
