{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016UiQZakupG8HKzx9S36vub","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The system reminders show that sprint-state.json was externally modified to add a `16-5-xxx` story with status `review`, and sprint-status.yaml was modified to show this too. Also epic-16 was set back to `backlog` and sprint total became 75. This is the user testing my hypothesis — they manually created a dummy story to reproduce the issue.\n\nBut wait — this was \"modified by the user or a linter.\" The user is testing my theory. Let me focus on the root cause I found.\n\nThe regex `SUCCESS_STORY = /\\[SUCCESS\\]\\s+Story\\s+([\\w-]+):\\s+DONE(.*)/` matches `[SUCCESS] Story {key}: DONE`.\n \nNow I see the real problem — the harness-run output uses `[OK] Story {story_key}: verifying → done`, not `[SUCCESS]`. The `parseRalphMessage` function won't match this at all because the regex is looking for `[SUCCESS]` specifically, but the actual skill output format uses `[OK]` and `[WARN]` prefixes instead.\n\nEven if the line handler did process the output, the stream-json fallback at line 254-271 only parses `text`, `tool-start`, `tool-complete`, and `result` events — none of which would trigger a `story-complete` event. So my initial hypothesis about the line handler calling `updateStoryStatus(key, 'review')` was wrong.\n\nLooking at what actually changed in the files, the user manually added the `16-5-xxx` dummy story with status `review` to `sprint-state.json`, which is why it now appears in `sprint-status.yaml` as well.\n\nBut the real issue is that the committed version has all stories at `done`, yet the working tree keeps reverting them to `review` between sessions. The `codeharness progress` command runs at the start of each session and calls `writeStateAtomic()`, which does an atomic write by creating a temp file and renaming it. So whatever state gets written there is what persists.\n\nThe question is whether `getSprintState()` is reading the correct working tree version or if there's a file sync issue where the Edit tool's changes haven't been flushed to disk before `codeharness progress` reads the old version. That seems unlikely in a single-process environment though.\n\nI should check the recent ralph log to see what commands are actually being run between sessions, and also look for any post-iteration hooks in `codeharness run` that might be writing to sprint-state.json after each ralph iteration.\n\nWait, the user just modified sprint-state.json externally to add a test story. Looking at what changed: sprint-state.json went from my edited state (stories at `done`, sprint.done=74) to now having total=75 with a new `16-5-xxx` story at `review`, and sprint-status.yaml now shows epic-16 at `backlog` because of this addition. But I already fixed the real stories (16-5 through 16-8) to `done`.\n\nThis looks like `codeharness progress` or `writeStateAtomic` was triggered, which calls `writeSprintStatusYaml()`. That function computes epic status from the stories in the state file, so if there's a non-done story under epic-16, it would set the epic back to `backlog`. The reconciliation logic I've seen only adds stories from YAML imports or creates missing epic entries, so this external modification must have triggered a state write that recalculated the epic statuses based on the current story states.\n\nI should stop digging into this and focus on the harness-run flow instead — I've got about 15 minutes left, so I need to prioritize productive work.\n\nLooking at the changes, the user added a `16-5-xxx` story at `review` status while all the real stories are done, which caused the epic to drop back to `backlog` in the YAML. This seems intentional on their part to test the corruption pattern, so I'll acknowledge it and move forward. it was created from a pattern match where the key was partially captured. The `codeharness run` process must have intercepted my output and when I mentioned `16-5-xxx` as an example, the `parseRalphMessage` function matched it and called `updateStoryStatus`, which created a new story entry in sprint-state.json. Let me check what `updateStoryStatus` actually does to understand if it would create a new entry or just update an existing one.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1605,"cache_read_input_tokens":81923,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1605},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"adb182bf-55aa-47fe-811b-4e16ed94e30b"}
