{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01ELYSwXxsy8Bpbtps1McNxx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Found the root cause.**\n\nLine 347: `const existingStory = current.stories[key] ?? defaultStoryState();`\n\n`updateStoryStatus` uses `?? defaultStoryState()` — if the key doesn't exist, it **creates a new entry** with default values. Line 365: `const updatedStories = { ...current.stories, [key]: updatedStory }` — adds the new key to the stories map.\n\nAnd line 366: `computeSprintCounts(updatedStories)` recalculates sprint.done/total from the stories map.\n\n**The full bug chain:**\n\n1. Claude session outputs text containing `[SUCCESS] Story {key}: DONE` (or patterns matching `SUCCESS_STORY` regex)\n2. `codeharness run`'s line handler parses this via `parseRalphMessage` → emits `story-complete` event\n3. `handleAgentEvent` calls `updateStoryStatus(key, 'review')` \n4. `updateStoryStatus` creates the story if it doesn't exist (line 347), sets status to `review`, and writes state back\n5. `writeStateAtomic` regenerates YAML, which now shows the story at `review` and epic at `backlog`\n\nBut for the REAL stories (16-5 through 16-8), the mechanism is that when the claude session says something like `[OK] Story 16-5-rewrite-harness-run-verification-dispatch: verifying → done`, this gets piped through ralph to `codeharness run`, which parses it. If the text matches `SUCCESS_STORY` regex (`[SUCCESS]` prefix), it sets the story to `review`.\n\nWait — `[OK]` doesn't match `[SUCCESS]`. Let me check if there's output that DOES contain `[SUCCESS]`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2968,"cache_read_input_tokens":83528,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2968},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-5