{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01LtAztoUAVMR7J36gpLsDkq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the bug in action! Two phantom stories have been created: `16-5-xxx` and `16-5-foo`. These were created because my text output (analyzing the bug) contained patterns like `[SUCCESS] Story 16-5-xxx: DONE` and `[SUCCESS] Story 16-5-foo: DONE` (from the test file `ralph.test.ts` that I was reading). The `parseRalphMessage` function in the ralph driver matched these patterns within the stream-json output and `updateStoryStatus` was called, creating new phantom entries.\n\nWait, but I didn't output `[SUCCESS]` in my text. \n\nLet me trace where `16-5-foo` actually came from by checking the test file more carefully — the test uses `1-1-foo`, not `16-5-foo`, so this pattern must have appeared somewhere else in the logged output, likely when the source code itself was being displayed as a tool result.\n\nWhen that TypeScript source gets embedded in JSON, the regex pattern with backslashes gets escaped again — so `\\[` becomes `\\\\[` in the JSON string representation. When the `parseRalphMessage` function tries to match against this escaped content, it won't find the actual `[SUCCESS]` pattern because the brackets are still escaped in the string.\n\nHowever, if the tool result contains actual test file content with the literal string `[SUCCESS] Story 1-1-foo: DONE`, that would match directly. The regex would extract the story key and update its status accordingly.\n\nSo the core issue is that when Claude sessions output or reference content containing `[SUCCESS] Story {key}: DONE` patterns—whether from test files, source code, or discussions—the `parseRalphMessage` regex matches these patterns within the JSON stream, triggering `updateStoryStatus` calls that either reset existing stories back to `review` or create phantom entries. For stories 16-5 through 16-8, this could happen if previous sessions output similar patterns, though they might use `[OK]` instead of `[SUCCESS]`.\n\nNow I'm wondering if ralph.sh itself is the source of these `[SUCCESS]` messages that are causing the unintended status updates.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":164,"cache_read_input_tokens":90070,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":164},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2610e689-589b-4ec2-8784-d06d07275472","uuid":"dbfc08db-f0a8-4519-8e98-a09602a617d2"}
